{{refimprove|date=March 2015}}
[[Image:The First Space Shuttle External Tank - GPN-2000-000051.jpg|right|200px|thumb|The first Space Shuttle External Tank (ET), the Main Propulsion Test Article (MPTA), rolls off the assembly line on September 9, 1977 at Michoud Assembly Facility in New Orleans, Louisiana.]]
The '''Main Propulsion Test Article External Tank''' ('''MPTA-ET''') was built by [[NASA]] to be used in conjunction with [[MPTA-098]] for structural tests of the [[Space Shuttle Main Engine]]s prior to construction of flyable craft. It rolled off the assembly line on September 9, 1977 at [[Michoud Assembly Facility]] in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]], and was then transported to the [[Stennis Space Center|National Space Technology Laboratories]] in southern Mississippi where it was used in the static test firing of the Shuttle's cluster of three main engines.

==Present status==
[[Image:SpaceShuttleAtSpaceCamp.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The [[Space Shuttle Pathfinder]] based at the [[U.S. Space & Rocket Center]].]]
The MPTA-ET is currently mated to the [[Space Shuttle Pathfinder]] mock-up, and two [[Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Booster|Advanced Solid Rocket Booster]] casings as a complete shuttle stack. The setup is on display at the [[U.S. Space & Rocket Center]] in [[Huntsville, Alabama]].<ref name="at110224">{{cite news |work=Atomic Toasters |title=Spaceheads: Space Shuttle Pathfinder |url=http://atomictoasters.com/2011/02/space-shuttle-pathfinder/ |date=February 24, 2011 |accessdate=July 6, 2011}}</ref>

